      type: "Enzyme replacement therapy (recombinant human alpha-galactosidase A)",
      action: "Recombinant form of the deficient alpha-galactosidase A enzyme; administered IV every 2 weeks, the exogenous enzyme is taken up by cells via mannose-6-phosphate receptors and delivered to lysosomes where it catabolizes accumulated Gb3 (globotriaosylceramide); reduces Gb3 deposition in vascular endothelium, cardiomyocytes, podocytes, and renal tubular cells; slows disease progression and stabilizes organ function when initiated before irreversible fibrotic changes",
      sideEffects: "Infusion-related reactions (rigors, fever, urticaria, chest tightness, dyspnea) in ~50-70% of patients during initial infusions -- managed with premedication and slower infusion rate; anti-drug antibody development (IgG antibodies in ~70% of classic males may reduce efficacy); rare anaphylaxis requiring desensitization protocol",
      contra: "Known anaphylactic hypersensitivity to agalsidase beta (absolute); caution with concurrent febuxostat (may theoretically reduce enzyme uptake); pregnancy class B (limited data but treatment is generally continued due to disease severity)",
